161.name: Ode to the Buidlers
161.description:
"Ode to the Buidlers" is a card created with a photographic technique known as "Photogrammetry." Photogrammetry involves scanning an areaand converting the photos and video into 3D points (aka point cloud). Those points are then rendered in a 3D program and editing, lighting, and other effects are added to create the final piece.

The entire process took around 2 months to complete, as I had to build the stage for the card. The hardest part was actually contacting the various buidlers in the space to ask for their permission to use their PFPs in the card. Some of the buidlers I was able to successfully contact were: 

1) Punk 6529  
2) Richerd - Manifold  
3) Pravjin - Deca  
4) Justin Trimble - Stability AI  
5) Ben Strauss - Transient Labs  
6) Snowfro - Artblocks  
7) Claire Silver - Accelerate Art  
8) Rayan - Oncyber  
9) Fonz - Tokenproof 
10) Norcalguy - ClickCreate

I was then able to order poster-sized prints of their PFPs. After obtaining the prints, I scouted for an area that fit my parameters for a successful scan. This part took me an entire day from morning until night. It is very difficult, because finding the perfect area will determine if the card will be loopable or not. Once I decided on the location, I came back on a different day, put up the posters, scanned the area, and then proceeded to the next month's work of editing and production. I also invested in a beefier video card for the sole purpose of creating this card.

I wanted to create a card that demonstrated my effort and dedication to the Memes. Not only high effort but also something new and different with a theme. The location this was shot at is Euljiro, Seoul, South Korea. This is an area where metal shop workers build components used in everyday machines and electronics. Not only that, but the sound recorded on the spot is also of the metal shop workers at their craft. And the PFPs are people who contribute to the web3 space with DApps we use in our everyday life.

Finally, the small blocks created through this technique can also be thought of as "The Buidler's Blocks."

281.description:
"Philosopher's Bitcoin" is a meme representing the journey of discovering the ultimate key to the perfect cryptocurrency ‚Äî a recipe for both financial and spiritual enlightenment. It symbolizes the modern-day alchemist's quest to unlock a secret formula for growth in both realms. This meme is said to bring luck in trading.

This concept draws inspiration from alchemy, specifically the Philosopher's Stone and the Rebis. The central figure combines both male and female elements, symbolizing the reconciliation of opposites ‚Äî spirit and matter, logic and emotion. The meme is adorned with cryptographic symbols and blockchain-inspired patterns.

Philosopher's Bitcoin aligns with the "Freedom to Transact" theme. "The Search for the Perfect Coin" emphasizes how cryptocurrency serves as the vehicle for achieving this freedom, facilitating transactions without barriers and enabling individuals to exercise control over their financial interactions.

For context, alchemy aimed at both material and spiritual transformation. Practically, alchemists sought to transmute base metals into gold, discover the Philosopher's Stone ‚Äî a substance that enables transmutation and grants immortality ‚Äî and develop early forms of medicine. Spiritually, alchemy was about personal transformation, mirroring the process of purifying the soul through stages of growth. It also sought to reconcile opposites like spirit and matter, male and female, light and dark, to achieve balance.

The Rebis (from the Latin res bina, meaning "dual matter") is the end product of the alchemical magnum opus or Great Work. After undergoing stages of decay and purification, opposing qualities are separated and then reunited in what is often described as the divine hermaphrodite ‚Äî a reconciliation of spirit and matter. This being embodies both male and female aspects, as symbolized by a single body with two heads, one male and one female.

Details like an embroidery of a unicorn, referencing Uniswap, and the planet Jupiter, symbolizing Solana traders, are incorporated to give nods to key elements in the crypto world. A gecko or salamander is also present, symbolizing both fire in alchemy and CoinGecko in crypto. These small symbols represent what makes a great trader ‚Äî wisdom, foresight, and a deep connection to the market. 

The number seven, present in the meme, holds significant symbolic importance in alchemy, especially in the context of the Rebis. In alchemical tradition, seven often represents the completion of a cycle, spiritual transformation, and the harmony of opposites. Alchemy associates seven classical planets with seven corresponding metals. The Sun (Sol) is associated with gold, symbolizing purity and enlightenment, while the Moon (Luna) is linked to silver, representing intuition and the feminine principle. Mercury (Mercurius) is tied to the metal mercury (quicksilver), symbolizing transformation and the union of spirit and matter. Venus corresponds to copper, symbolizing beauty and harmony, while Mars is linked to iron, representing strength and masculine energy. Jupiter is associated with tin, symbolizing wisdom and growth, and Saturn corresponds to lead, representing transformation and the base material to be purified. These seven elements must be harmonized and transmuted during the alchemical process.

285.description:
This artwork critiques centralized power while celebrating the ideals of decentralization. The phrase ‚ÄúHic Situs Imperium Centrale‚Äù is a creative adaptation of the Latin epitaph ‚ÄúHic Situs Est,‚Äù meaning ‚ÄúHere Lies.‚Äù Traditionally found on Roman tombstones, it conveys finality and legacy. By adding ‚ÄúImperium Centrale‚Äù‚Äî‚ÄúCentral Power‚Äù‚Äîthe phrase symbolizes the burial of central authority, with the Roman Empire serving as a historical reference for such systems.

The tulip used in the composition resembles the Semper Augustus, the rarest and most valuable tulip in history. During the 17th-century Tulip Mania, it embodied wealth, greed, and colonial power. Although the original Semper Augustus is extinct, this tulip‚Äîfound in the garden of Toronto‚Äôs City Hall‚Äîadds a playful and rebellious twist, subtly reclaiming control from institutional authority.

The composition is carefully designed with shadows connecting each element‚Äîthe skull, vase, and tulip‚Äîcreating a visual loop that guides the viewer‚Äôs gaze. The skull represents mortality, the vase symbolizes the rigidity of authority, the tulip reflects the fragility of beauty and power, and the shadows emphasize the inevitable connection between these concepts. Through this thoughtful arrangement, the artwork critiques control systems while embracing transformation, impermanence, and decentralized freedom.

Stone becomes scripture!
